<h1>5.1 Order of subject, object, and verb</h1>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes-syntactic-relation-labels">Relevant postag
codes / syntactic relation labels</h2>
<p><strong>Syntactic label:</strong></p>
<p>The main predicate in the sentence is annotated as PRED, the subject
- as SBJ, and the object - as OBJ. If the element is participating in
coordination, ’_CO’ is added to the syntactic label.</p>
<p><strong>Example</strong>: καὶ οἱ τέκτονες πεπληρώκασι τοὺς μισθούς·
(kaì hoí téktones peplērṓkasi toùs misthoús) - <em>and the builders have
paid the wages</em> (bgu.16.2607, l. 23-24, s. 14)</p>
<p></p><div style="height:300px; " data-treeid="1" class="sentence-tree tf-tree tf-result" data-json=""></div><p></p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary:</h2>
<p>In papyri, the dominant order of the major constituents in the
sentence varies according to the text type. Verbal-initial patterns are
strongly represented in private and legal texts, while petitions are
abundant with Subject-initial order patterns.</p>
<h2 id="examples-from-papygreek-corpus">Example(s) from PapyGreek
corpus:</h2>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion:</h2>
<h3 id="classical-greek">Classical Greek</h3>
<p>The leading explanation for the order patterns of the major sentence
constituents is that it is pragmatically determined and fixed. The basic
pattern suggested by Helma Dik (<span class="citation" data-cites="dik1995">(<strong>dik1995?</strong>)</span>, <span class="citation" data-cites="dik2007">(Dik 2007)</span>) is the
following:</p>
<p><em>(Setting) - Topic - Focus - Verb - Remainder</em></p>
<p>Within this framework, permutations and variations are possible, in
order to link individual utterances in the discourse and contrast them
against, or present as a continuation of, a previously stated idea <span class="citation" data-cites="celano2014">(Celano 2014a)</span>.</p>
<h3 id="shift-in-koine-towards-vso">Shift in Koine towards VSO</h3>
<p><span class="citation" data-cites="horrocks2007">Horrocks
(2007)</span> discusses the establishment of VSO and SVO patterns as
most frequent ordering of the major sentence constituents in Koine, in
contrast to the predominant verb-final structures in Classical Greek,
and proposes an explanation for this shift based on the role of clitics.
In verb-final sentences, it is possible for clitics, due to their
tendency to cluster in second position (Wackernagel (1892)), to
sometimes occur too far away from the verb that governs them, putting a
strain on the attention of the reader/listener. A possible solution to
this “problem” can be achieved by displacing the clitic from its second
position and moving it directly after the verbal head. In the
Hellenistic period, a “compromise” between these two options starts to
appear in the form of the pattern <em>Verb + clitic + Subject +
Object</em>.</p>
<h3 id="new-testament-greek">New Testament Greek</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Horrocks 1990/2007? <span class="citation" data-cites="horrocks2007">Horrocks (2007)</span>: Shift in Koine towards
VSO order and the role of clitic pronouns</p></li>
<li><p>Dik’s Pragmatic Paradigm cannot be tested through the means of
treebanking, but it should be presented briefly as one of the leading
contenders for explanation</p></li>
<li><p>Topic and focus -discussion, Dik 1995: (Setting) - Topic - Focus
- Verb - Remainder<br>
<span class="citation" data-cites="holton2019">Holton et al.
(2019)</span>: Topic and focus can be defined in a variety of ways:
referring to prosodic, pragmatic, semantic and/or syntactic factors, and
in Medieval and Early Modern Greek, only prosodic properties could
determine topical/focal elements, but these are not accessible to us
anymore; the same applies to Greek in the papyri, naturally<br>
<span class="citation" data-cites="celano2014">Celano (2014a)</span>:
Greek topic and focus structures are more complicated than what Dik
suggested</p></li>
<li><p>New Testament: <span class="citation" data-cites="pitts2022">Pitts (2022)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="kwong2005">Kwong (2005)</span></p></li>
<li><p>Celano - treebank-based study of word order in prose: “A
computational study on preverbal and postverbal accusative object nouns
and pronouns in Ancient Greek”</p></li>
